    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm working on an embedded c++ project for an automotive control unit and we're seeing a slow memory leak. the system runs fine for a few hours but then eventually runs out of available ram and crashes. i don't see any obvious missing deletes in my main loop. how should i go about systematically finding where the leak is happening?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "For an embedded C++ project, the best approach is to use memory profiling tools, even if your target hardware is resource-constrained; you might need to emulate or use a debug build on a host machine first. If that's too heavy, start by instrumenting your code to track allocations and deallocations at critical points, perhaps by wrapping `new` and `delete` with counters. Then, you can use a heap snapshotting technique, where you take a memory profile at startup and then periodically (e.g., every hour) and compare it to see which allocations are growing without corresponding frees. This systematic tracking should point you toward the rogue allocation site.",
      "source": "target",
