    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "the heap snapshotting thing makes sense. i've got some telemetry data from the last few runs that shows the heap usage is creeping up specifically during the sensor polling routine, but when i look at the code for that module, everything looks pretty standard. there aren't any obvious heap allocations happening inside the loop. why would it be growing if there's nothing being explicitly allocated?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A creeping leak during sensor polling, even without explicit `new` calls in the loop, often points to dynamic resources being held by objects that are themselves allocating memory, or perhaps leaks within underlying library calls. It could be that a sensor driver function is internally allocating buffers (like for data conversion or logging) and failing to release them before the next poll. You need to scrutinize the *dependencies* of your polling routine, not just the loop body itself. Try to trace every function call within that sensor polling routine to see if any of them return pointers or manage dynamically allocated structures.",
      "source": "target",
