    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i checked the driver calls and a few of them are calling into a third-party utility for data processing. it looks like it's creating some temporary buffer objects. it's hard to tell if the library is properly cleaning up after itself or if it’s just \"losing\" those pointers somewhere. it feels like these bugs are just hiding in the background where I can't easily see them during a standard debug session. what's the best way to hunt down these kinds of elusive, hidden issues when you can't see the source code of the driver?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When the leak is hidden inside a third-party library, you are essentially in a black box situation, which is frustrating. The most effective strategy here is to \"wrap\" the external calls—create a thin wrapper layer around every function in that utility library that touches memory. Inside your wrapper, implement aggressive logging or, better yet, use a custom memory allocation hook (if the library uses standard C++ allocation routines) to track every single allocation made *through* that wrapper. If the library allocates memory, your wrapper will log it, and you can then track which specific library function is responsible for the growing count.",
      "source": "target",
